---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="Paul Drew — esports founder, tech company builder, solar power enthusiast, lifelong gamer. The person behind SolarCurve and the House of Flamp."
>
  <Nav />

  <main class="px-6 md:px-10 py-10 max-w-3xl mx-auto">
    <h1 class="text-2xl font-medium text-star mb-8">About</h1>

    <picture>
      <source srcset="/images/paul_commodore_adult.webp" type="image/webp" />
      <img
        src="/images/paul_commodore_adult.jpg"
        alt="Paul Drew with a Commodore 64"
        width="800"
        height="600"
        class="rounded-lg border border-border mb-8 w-full max-w-md"
      />
    </picture>

    <div class="space-y-5 text-[15px] text-bright leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        I'm Paul. This is the House of Flamp — my corner of the internet in
        Flower Mound, TX.
      </p>
      <p>
        The whole thing started when Hasbro ran a contest to name the next Care
        Bear and a six-year-old won a Commodore 64 for suggesting "Tender Heart."
        No instructions, no saved games — just a keyboard, a blank screen, and
        weeks-long marathons keeping the machine powered on so my text-based RPGs
        wouldn't vanish. That machine taught me patience with hard problems, and
        I've been chasing the feeling of <em>something finally working</em> ever since.
      </p>
      <p>
        No college degree, no map — just work. I went from sacking groceries and
        running the McDonald's prep line to riding the printing industry's leap
        from Exacto knives to digital production, then across the wall into tech
        proper. I spent a decade building a multi-million dollar "Content
        Logistics" business in the messy space between the agencies that create
        content and the providers that host it, and I've been at this for thirty
        years now. The credential is rarely the thing. Showing up is the thing.
      </p>
      <p>
        Along the way I founded the Texas Area Untouchables (TAU), competed in
        CAL-Invite and at CPL LANs, and ran gaming cafes that helped build DFW's
        esports infrastructure from 2000–2005 — years before "esports" was a word
        anyone's parents knew. I still play. FPS games were my gateway and remain
        my stress relief of choice.
      </p>
      <p>
        The current obsession is the roof: 28.9 kW of solar — 65 panels feeding
        3 Tesla inverters — generating more than the house uses. The
        <a href="/solar" class="text-solar-300 hover:underline">solar journey</a>
        section tracks the whole project from contract to live data, and the
        data-nerd phase is just getting started.
      </p>
      <p>
        The name SolarCurve? It was a photo-retouching technique long before it
        was a rooftop. Funny how these things work out.
      </p>
      <p class="text-dim text-sm">
        Find me on
        <a href="https://steamcommunity.com/id/solarcurve" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-solar-300 hover:underline">Steam</a>
        or
        <a href="https://github.com/SolarCurve" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-solar-300 hover:underline">GitHub</a>,
        or dig through the
        <a href="https://solarcurve.blogspot.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-solar-300 hover:underline">old blog archive</a>
        going back to 2009.
      </p>
    </div>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
